DUODECIMOES.--These include the smaller whales. I. The Huzza Porpoise.          QHBQRPVZBRF.--Gurfr vapyhqr gur fznyyre junyrf. V. Gur Uhmmn Cbecbvfr.
II. The Algerine Porpoise. III. The Mealy-mouthed Porpoise.                     VV. Gur Nytrevar Cbecbvfr. VVV. Gur Zrnyl-zbhgurq Cbecbvfr.
                                                                                
To those who have not chanced specially to study the subject, it may            Gb gubfr jub unir abg punaprq fcrpvnyyl gb fghql gur fhowrpg, vg znl
possibly seem strange, that fishes not commonly exceeding four or five          cbffvoyl frrz fgenatr, gung svfurf abg pbzzbayl rkprrqvat sbhe be svir
feet should be marshalled among WHALES--a word, which, in the popular           srrg fubhyq or znefunyyrq nzbat JUNYRF--n jbeq, juvpu, va gur cbchyne
sense, always conveys an idea of hugeness. But the creatures set                frafr, nyjnlf pbairlf na vqrn bs uhtrarff. Ohg gur perngherf frg
down above as Duodecimoes are infallibly whales, by the terms of my             qbja nobir nf Qhbqrpvzbrf ner vasnyyvoyl junyrf, ol gur grezf bs zl
definition of what a whale is--i.e. a spouting fish, with a horizontal          qrsvavgvba bs jung n junyr vf--v.r. n fcbhgvat svfu, jvgu n ubevmbagny
tail.                                                                           gnvy.
                                                                                
