CHAPTER 33. The Specksynder.                                                    PUNCGRE 33. Gur Fcrpxflaqre.
                                                                                
                                                                                
Concerning the officers of the whale-craft, this seems as good a place          Pbapreavat gur bssvpref bs gur junyr-pensg, guvf frrzf nf tbbq n cynpr
as any to set down a little domestic peculiarity on ship-board, arising         nf nal gb frg qbja n yvggyr qbzrfgvp crphyvnevgl ba fuvc-obneq, nevfvat
from the existence of the harpooneer class of officers, a class unknown         sebz gur rkvfgrapr bs gur unecbbarre pynff bs bssvpref, n pynff haxabja
of course in any other marine than the whale-fleet.                             bs pbhefr va nal bgure znevar guna gur junyr-syrrg.
                                                                                
The large importance attached to the harpooneer's vocation is evinced           Gur ynetr vzcbegnapr nggnpurq gb gur unecbbarre'f ibpngvba vf rivaprq
by the fact, that originally in the old Dutch Fishery, two centuries            ol gur snpg, gung bevtvanyyl va gur byq Qhgpu Svfurel, gjb praghevrf
and more ago, the command of a whale ship was not wholly lodged in              naq zber ntb, gur pbzznaq bs n junyr fuvc jnf abg jubyyl ybqtrq va
the person now called the captain, but was divided between him and an           gur crefba abj pnyyrq gur pncgnva, ohg jnf qvivqrq orgjrra uvz naq na
officer called the Specksynder. Literally this word means Fat-Cutter;           bssvpre pnyyrq gur Fcrpxflaqre. Yvgrenyyl guvf jbeq zrnaf Sng-Phggre;
usage, however, in time made it equivalent to Chief Harpooneer. In              hfntr, ubjrire, va gvzr znqr vg rdhvinyrag gb Puvrs Unecbbarre. Va
those days, the captain's authority was restricted to the navigation            gubfr qnlf, gur pncgnva'f nhgubevgl jnf erfgevpgrq gb gur anivtngvba
and general management of the vessel; while over the whale-hunting              naq trareny znantrzrag bs gur irffry; juvyr bire gur junyr-uhagvat
department and all its concerns, the Specksynder or Chief Harpooneer            qrcnegzrag naq nyy vgf pbapreaf, gur Fcrpxflaqre be Puvrs Unecbbarre
reigned supreme. In the British Greenland Fishery, under the corrupted          ervtarq fhcerzr. Va gur Oevgvfu Terraynaq Svfurel, haqre gur pbeehcgrq
title of Specksioneer, this old Dutch official is still retained, but           gvgyr bs Fcrpxfvbarre, guvf byq Qhgpu bssvpvny vf fgvyy ergnvarq, ohg
his former dignity is sadly abridged. At present he ranks simply                uvf sbezre qvtavgl vf fnqyl noevqtrq. Ng cerfrag ur enaxf fvzcyl
