CHAPTER 35. The Mast-Head.                                                      PUNCGRE 35. Gur Znfg-Urnq.
                                                                                
                                                                                
It was during the more pleasant weather, that in due rotation with the          Vg jnf qhevat gur zber cyrnfnag jrngure, gung va qhr ebgngvba jvgu gur
other seamen my first mast-head came round.                                     bgure frnzra zl svefg znfg-urnq pnzr ebhaq.
                                                                                
In most American whalemen the mast-heads are manned almost                      Va zbfg Nzrevpna junyrzra gur znfg-urnqf ner znaarq nyzbfg
simultaneously with the vessel's leaving her port; even though she may          fvzhygnarbhfyl jvgu gur irffry'f yrnivat ure cbeg; rira gubhtu fur znl
have fifteen thousand miles, and more, to sail ere reaching her proper          unir svsgrra gubhfnaq zvyrf, naq zber, gb fnvy rer ernpuvat ure cebcre
cruising ground. And if, after a three, four, or five years' voyage             pehvfvat tebhaq. Naq vs, nsgre n guerr, sbhe, be svir lrnef' iblntr
she is drawing nigh home with anything empty in her--say, an empty vial         fur vf qenjvat avtu ubzr jvgu nalguvat rzcgl va ure--fnl, na rzcgl ivny
even--then, her mast-heads are kept manned to the last; and not till her        rira--gura, ure znfg-urnqf ner xrcg znaarq gb gur ynfg; naq abg gvyy ure
skysail-poles sail in among the spires of the port, does she altogether         fxlfnvy-cbyrf fnvy va nzbat gur fcverf bs gur cbeg, qbrf fur nygbtrgure
relinquish the hope of capturing one whale more.                                eryvadhvfu gur ubcr bs pncghevat bar junyr zber.
                                                                                
Now, as the business of standing mast-heads, ashore or afloat, is a very        Abj, nf gur ohfvarff bs fgnaqvat znfg-urnqf, nfuber be nsybng, vf n irel
ancient and interesting one, let us in some measure expatiate here.             napvrag naq vagrerfgvat bar, yrg hf va fbzr zrnfher rkcngvngr urer.
I take it, that the earliest standers of mast-heads were the old                V gnxr vg, gung gur rneyvrfg fgnaqref bs znfg-urnqf jrer gur byq
Egyptians; because, in all my researches, I find none prior to them.            Rtlcgvnaf; orpnhfr, va nyy zl erfrnepurf, V svaq abar cevbe gb gurz.
For though their progenitors, the builders of Babel, must doubtless, by         Sbe gubhtu gurve cebtravgbef, gur ohvyqref bs Onory, zhfg qbhogyrff, ol
their tower, have intended to rear the loftiest mast-head in all Asia,          gurve gbjre, unir vagraqrq gb erne gur ybsgvrfg znfg-urnq va nyy Nfvn,
or Africa either; yet (ere the final truck was put to it) as that great         be Nsevpn rvgure; lrg (rer gur svany gehpx jnf chg gb vg) nf gung terng
stone mast of theirs may be said to have gone by the board, in the dread        fgbar znfg bs gurvef znl or fnvq gb unir tbar ol gur obneq, va gur qernq
gale of God's wrath; therefore, we cannot give these Babel builders             tnyr bs Tbq'f jengu; gurersber, jr pnaabg tvir gurfr Onory ohvyqref
priority over the Egyptians. And that the Egyptians were a nation of            cevbevgl bire gur Rtlcgvnaf. Naq gung gur Rtlcgvnaf jrer n angvba bs
mast-head standers, is an assertion based upon the general belief among         znfg-urnq fgnaqref, vf na nffregvba onfrq hcba gur trareny oryvrs nzbat
archaeologists, that the first pyramids were founded for astronomical           nepunrbybtvfgf, gung gur svefg clenzvqf jrer sbhaqrq sbe nfgebabzvpny
purposes: a theory singularly supported by the peculiar stair-like              checbfrf: n gurbel fvathyneyl fhccbegrq ol gur crphyvne fgnve-yvxr
formation of all four sides of those edifices; whereby, with prodigious         sbezngvba bs nyy sbhe fvqrf bs gubfr rqvsvprf; jurerol, jvgu cebqvtvbhf
long upliftings of their legs, those old astronomers were wont to mount         ybat hcyvsgvatf bs gurve yrtf, gubfr byq nfgebabzref jrer jbag gb zbhag
to the apex, and sing out for new stars; even as the look-outs of a             gb gur ncrk, naq fvat bhg sbe arj fgnef; rira nf gur ybbx-bhgf bs n
modern ship sing out for a sail, or a whale just bearing in sight. In           zbqrea fuvc fvat bhg sbe n fnvy, be n junyr whfg ornevat va fvtug. Va
Saint Stylites, the famous Christian hermit of old times, who built him         Fnvag Fglyvgrf, gur snzbhf Puevfgvna urezvg bs byq gvzrf, jub ohvyg uvz
a lofty stone pillar in the desert and spent the whole latter portion of        n ybsgl fgbar cvyyne va gur qrfreg naq fcrag gur jubyr ynggre cbegvba bs
his life on its summit, hoisting his food from the ground with a                uvf yvsr ba vgf fhzzvg, ubvfgvat uvf sbbq sebz gur tebhaq jvgu n
tackle; in him we have a remarkable instance of a dauntless                     gnpxyr; va uvz jr unir n erznexnoyr vafgnapr bs n qnhagyrff
