CHAPTER 60. The Line.                                                           PUNCGRE 60. Gur Yvar.
                                                                                
                                                                                
With reference to the whaling scene shortly to be described, as well as         Jvgu ersrerapr gb gur junyvat fprar fubegyl gb or qrfpevorq, nf jryy nf
for the better understanding of all similar scenes elsewhere presented,         sbe gur orggre haqrefgnaqvat bs nyy fvzvyne fprarf ryfrjurer cerfragrq,
I have here to speak of the magical, sometimes horrible whale-line.             V unir urer gb fcrnx bs gur zntvpny, fbzrgvzrf ubeevoyr junyr-yvar.
                                                                                
The line originally used in the fishery was of the best hemp, slightly          Gur yvar bevtvanyyl hfrq va gur svfurel jnf bs gur orfg urzc, fyvtugyl
vapoured with tar, not impregnated with it, as in the case of ordinary          incbherq jvgu gne, abg vzcertangrq jvgu vg, nf va gur pnfr bs beqvanel
ropes; for while tar, as ordinarily used, makes the hemp more pliable to        ebcrf; sbe juvyr gne, nf beqvanevyl hfrq, znxrf gur urzc zber cyvnoyr gb
the rope-maker, and also renders the rope itself more convenient to the         gur ebcr-znxre, naq nyfb eraqref gur ebcr vgfrys zber pbairavrag gb gur
sailor for common ship use; yet, not only would the ordinary quantity           fnvybe sbe pbzzba fuvc hfr; lrg, abg bayl jbhyq gur beqvanel dhnagvgl
too much stiffen the whale-line for the close coiling to which it must          gbb zhpu fgvssra gur junyr-yvar sbe gur pybfr pbvyvat gb juvpu vg zhfg
be subjected; but as most seamen are beginning to learn, tar in general         or fhowrpgrq; ohg nf zbfg frnzra ner ortvaavat gb yrnea, gne va trareny
by no means adds to the rope's durability or strength, however much it          ol ab zrnaf nqqf gb gur ebcr'f qhenovyvgl be fgeratgu, ubjrire zhpu vg
may give it compactness and gloss.                                              znl tvir vg pbzcnpgarff naq tybff.
                                                                                
Of late years the Manilla rope has in the American fishery almost               Bs yngr lrnef gur Znavyyn ebcr unf va gur Nzrevpna svfurel nyzbfg
entirely superseded hemp as a material for whale-lines; for, though not         ragveryl fhcrefrqrq urzc nf n zngrevny sbe junyr-yvarf; sbe, gubhtu abg
so durable as hemp, it is stronger, and far more soft and elastic; and          fb qhenoyr nf urzc, vg vf fgebatre, naq sne zber fbsg naq rynfgvp; naq
I will add (since there is an aesthetics in all things), is much more           V jvyy nqq (fvapr gurer vf na nrfgurgvpf va nyy guvatf), vf zhpu zber
handsome and becoming to the boat, than hemp. Hemp is a dusky, dark             unaqfbzr naq orpbzvat gb gur obng, guna urzc. Urzc vf n qhfxl, qnex
fellow, a sort of Indian; but Manilla is as a golden-haired Circassian          sryybj, n fbeg bs Vaqvna; ohg Znavyyn vf nf n tbyqra-unverq Pvepnffvna
to behold.                                                                      gb orubyq.
                                                                                
The whale-line is only two-thirds of an inch in thickness. At first             Gur junyr-yvar vf bayl gjb-guveqf bs na vapu va guvpxarff. Ng svefg
sight, you would not think it so strong as it really is. By experiment          fvtug, lbh jbhyq abg guvax vg fb fgebat nf vg ernyyl vf. Ol rkcrevzrag
its one and fifty yarns will each suspend a weight of one hundred and           vgf bar naq svsgl lneaf jvyy rnpu fhfcraq n jrvtug bs bar uhaqerq naq
twenty pounds; so that the whole rope will bear a strain nearly equal           gjragl cbhaqf; fb gung gur jubyr ebcr jvyy orne n fgenva arneyl rdhny
to three tons. In length, the common sperm whale-line measures something        gb guerr gbaf. Va yratgu, gur pbzzba fcrez junyr-yvar zrnfherf fbzrguvat
over two hundred fathoms. Towards the stern of the boat it is spirally          bire gjb uhaqerq sngubzf. Gbjneqf gur fgrea bs gur obng vg vf fcvenyyl
coiled away in the tub, not like the worm-pipe of a still though, but so        pbvyrq njnl va gur gho, abg yvxr gur jbez-cvcr bs n fgvyy gubhtu, ohg fb
as to form one round, cheese-shaped mass of densely bedded "sheaves," or        nf gb sbez bar ebhaq, purrfr-funcrq znff bs qrafryl orqqrq "furnirf," be
layers of concentric spiralizations, without any hollow but the "heart,"        ynlref bs pbapragevp fcvenyvmngvbaf, jvgubhg nal ubyybj ohg gur "urneg,"
or minute vertical tube formed at the axis of the cheese. As the least          be zvahgr iregvpny ghor sbezrq ng gur nkvf bs gur purrfr. Nf gur yrnfg
tangle or kink in the coiling would, in running out, infallibly take            gnatyr be xvax va gur pbvyvat jbhyq, va ehaavat bhg, vasnyyvoyl gnxr
somebody's arm, leg, or entire body off, the utmost precaution is used          fbzrobql'f nez, yrt, be ragver obql bss, gur hgzbfg cerpnhgvba vf hfrq
in stowing the line in its tub. Some harpooneers will consume almost an         va fgbjvat gur yvar va vgf gho. Fbzr unecbbarref jvyy pbafhzr nyzbfg na
entire morning in this business, carrying the line high aloft and then          ragver zbeavat va guvf ohfvarff, pneelvat gur yvar uvtu nybsg naq gura
reeving it downwards through a block towards the tub, so as in the act          errivat vg qbjajneqf guebhtu n oybpx gbjneqf gur gho, fb nf va gur npg
of coiling to free it from all possible wrinkles and twists.                    bs pbvyvat gb serr vg sebz nyy cbffvoyr jevaxyrf naq gjvfgf.
                                                                                
In the English boats two tubs are used instead of one; the same line            Va gur Ratyvfu obngf gjb ghof ner hfrq vafgrnq bs bar; gur fnzr yvar
being continuously coiled in both tubs. There is some advantage in this;        orvat pbagvahbhfyl pbvyrq va obgu ghof. Gurer vf fbzr nqinagntr va guvf;
because these twin-tubs being so small they fit more readily into the           orpnhfr gurfr gjva-ghof orvat fb fznyy gurl svg zber ernqvyl vagb gur
boat, and do not strain it so much; whereas, the American tub, nearly           obng, naq qb abg fgenva vg fb zhpu; jurernf, gur Nzrevpna gho, arneyl
three feet in diameter and of proportionate depth, makes a rather bulky         guerr srrg va qvnzrgre naq bs cebcbegvbangr qrcgu, znxrf n engure ohyxl
freight for a craft whose planks are but one half-inch in thickness; for        servtug sbe n pensg jubfr cynaxf ner ohg bar unys-vapu va guvpxarff; sbe
the bottom of the whale-boat is like critical ice, which will bear up           gur obggbz bs gur junyr-obng vf yvxr pevgvpny vpr, juvpu jvyy orne hc
a considerable distributed weight, but not very much of a concentrated          n pbafvqrenoyr qvfgevohgrq jrvtug, ohg abg irel zhpu bs n pbapragengrq
one. When the painted canvas cover is clapped on the American line-tub,         bar. Jura gur cnvagrq pnainf pbire vf pynccrq ba gur Nzrevpna yvar-gho,
