CHAPTER 62. The Dart.                                                           PUNCGRE 62. Gur Qneg.
                                                                                
                                                                                
A word concerning an incident in the last chapter.                              N jbeq pbapreavat na vapvqrag va gur ynfg puncgre.
                                                                                
According to the invariable usage of the fishery, the whale-boat pushes         Nppbeqvat gb gur vainevnoyr hfntr bs gur svfurel, gur junyr-obng chfurf
off from the ship, with the headsman or whale-killer as temporary               bss sebz gur fuvc, jvgu gur urnqfzna be junyr-xvyyre nf grzcbenel
steersman, and the harpooneer or whale-fastener pulling the foremost            fgrrefzna, naq gur unecbbarre be junyr-snfgrare chyyvat gur sberzbfg
oar, the one known as the harpooneer-oar. Now it needs a strong, nervous        bne, gur bar xabja nf gur unecbbarre-bne. Abj vg arrqf n fgebat, areibhf
arm to strike the first iron into the fish; for often, in what is called        nez gb fgevxr gur svefg veba vagb gur svfu; sbe bsgra, va jung vf pnyyrq
a long dart, the heavy implement has to be flung to the distance of             n ybat qneg, gur urnil vzcyrzrag unf gb or syhat gb gur qvfgnapr bs
twenty or thirty feet. But however prolonged and exhausting the chase,          gjragl be guvegl srrg. Ohg ubjrire cebybatrq naq rkunhfgvat gur punfr,
the harpooneer is expected to pull his oar meanwhile to the uttermost;          gur unecbbarre vf rkcrpgrq gb chyy uvf bne zrnajuvyr gb gur hggrezbfg;
indeed, he is expected to set an example of superhuman activity to the          vaqrrq, ur vf rkcrpgrq gb frg na rknzcyr bs fhcreuhzna npgvivgl gb gur
rest, not only by incredible rowing, but by repeated loud and intrepid          erfg, abg bayl ol vaperqvoyr ebjvat, ohg ol ercrngrq ybhq naq vagercvq
exclamations; and what it is to keep shouting at the top of one's               rkpynzngvbaf; naq jung vg vf gb xrrc fubhgvat ng gur gbc bs bar'f
compass, while all the other muscles are strained and half started--what        pbzcnff, juvyr nyy gur bgure zhfpyrf ner fgenvarq naq unys fgnegrq--jung
that is none know but those who have tried it. For one, I cannot bawl           gung vf abar xabj ohg gubfr jub unir gevrq vg. Sbe bar, V pnaabg onjy
very heartily and work very recklessly at one and the same time. In this        irel urnegvyl naq jbex irel erpxyrffyl ng bar naq gur fnzr gvzr. Va guvf
straining, bawling state, then, with his back to the fish, all at once          fgenvavat, onjyvat fgngr, gura, jvgu uvf onpx gb gur svfu, nyy ng bapr
the exhausted harpooneer hears the exciting cry--"Stand up, and give it         gur rkunhfgrq unecbbarre urnef gur rkpvgvat pel--"Fgnaq hc, naq tvir vg
to him!" He now has to drop and secure his oar, turn round on his               gb uvz!" Ur abj unf gb qebc naq frpher uvf bne, ghea ebhaq ba uvf
centre half way, seize his harpoon from the crotch, and with what little        prager unys jnl, frvmr uvf unecbba sebz gur pebgpu, naq jvgu jung yvggyr
strength may remain, he essays to pitch it somehow into the whale. No           fgeratgu znl erznva, ur rffnlf gb cvgpu vg fbzrubj vagb gur junyr. Ab
wonder, taking the whole fleet of whalemen in a body, that out of fifty         jbaqre, gnxvat gur jubyr syrrg bs junyrzra va n obql, gung bhg bs svsgl
fair chances for a dart, not five are successful; no wonder that so many        snve punaprf sbe n qneg, abg svir ner fhpprffshy; ab jbaqre gung fb znal
hapless harpooneers are madly cursed and disrated; no wonder that some          uncyrff unecbbarref ner znqyl phefrq naq qvfengrq; ab jbaqre gung fbzr
of them actually burst their blood-vessels in the boat; no wonder that          bs gurz npghnyyl ohefg gurve oybbq-irffryf va gur obng; ab jbaqre gung
some sperm whalemen are absent four years with four barrels; no wonder          fbzr fcrez junyrzra ner nofrag sbhe lrnef jvgu sbhe oneeryf; ab jbaqre
that to many ship owners, whaling is but a losing concern; for it is the        gung gb znal fuvc bjaref, junyvat vf ohg n ybfvat pbaprea; sbe vg vf gur
harpooneer that makes the voyage, and if you take the breath out of his         unecbbarre gung znxrf gur iblntr, naq vs lbh gnxr gur oerngu bhg bs uvf
body how can you expect to find it there when most wanted!                      obql ubj pna lbh rkcrpg gb svaq vg gurer jura zbfg jnagrq!
                                                                                
Again, if the dart be successful, then at the second critical instant,          Ntnva, vs gur qneg or fhpprffshy, gura ng gur frpbaq pevgvpny vafgnag,
that is, when the whale starts to run, the boatheader and harpooneer            gung vf, jura gur junyr fgnegf gb eha, gur obngurnqre naq unecbbarre
likewise start to running fore and aft, to the imminent jeopardy of             yvxrjvfr fgneg gb ehaavat sber naq nsg, gb gur vzzvarag wrbcneql bs
themselves and every one else. It is then they change places; and               gurzfryirf naq rirel bar ryfr. Vg vf gura gurl punatr cynprf; naq
the headsman, the chief officer of the little craft, takes his proper           gur urnqfzna, gur puvrs bssvpre bs gur yvggyr pensg, gnxrf uvf cebcre
station in the bows of the boat.                                                fgngvba va gur objf bs gur obng.
                                                                                
Now, I care not who maintains the contrary, but all this is both foolish        Abj, V pner abg jub znvagnvaf gur pbagenel, ohg nyy guvf vf obgu sbbyvfu
and unnecessary. The headsman should stay in the bows from first to             naq haarprffnel. Gur urnqfzna fubhyq fgnl va gur objf sebz svefg gb
last; he should both dart the harpoon and the lance, and no rowing              ynfg; ur fubhyq obgu qneg gur unecbba naq gur ynapr, naq ab ebjvat
whatever should be expected of him, except under circumstances obvious          jungrire fubhyq or rkcrpgrq bs uvz, rkprcg haqre pvephzfgnaprf boivbhf
to any fisherman. I know that this would sometimes involve a slight loss        gb nal svfurezna. V xabj gung guvf jbhyq fbzrgvzrf vaibyir n fyvtug ybff
of speed in the chase; but long experience in various whalemen of more          bs fcrrq va gur punfr; ohg ybat rkcrevrapr va inevbhf junyrzra bs zber
than one nation has convinced me that in the vast majority of failures          guna bar angvba unf pbaivaprq zr gung va gur infg znwbevgl bs snvyherf
in the fishery, it has not by any means been so much the speed of the           va gur svfurel, vg unf abg ol nal zrnaf orra fb zhpu gur fcrrq bs gur
whale as the before described exhaustion of the harpooneer that has             junyr nf gur orsber qrfpevorq rkunhfgvba bs gur unecbbarre gung unf
caused them.                                                                    pnhfrq gurz.
                                                                                
To insure the greatest efficiency in the dart, the harpooneers of this          Gb vafher gur terngrfg rssvpvrapl va gur qneg, gur unecbbarref bs guvf
world must start to their feet from out of idleness, and not from out of        jbeyq zhfg fgneg gb gurve srrg sebz bhg bs vqyrarff, naq abg sebz bhg bs
toil.                                                                           gbvy.
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
CHAPTER 63. The Crotch.                                                         PUNCGRE 63. Gur Pebgpu.
                                                                                
                                                                                
Out of the trunk, the branches grow; out of them, the twigs. So, in             Bhg bs gur gehax, gur oenapurf tebj; bhg bs gurz, gur gjvtf. Fb, va
productive subjects, grow the chapters.                                         cebqhpgvir fhowrpgf, tebj gur puncgref.
                                                                                
The crotch alluded to on a previous page deserves independent mention.          Gur pebgpu nyyhqrq gb ba n cerivbhf cntr qrfreirf vaqrcraqrag zragvba.
It is a notched stick of a peculiar form, some two feet in length, which        Vg vf n abgpurq fgvpx bs n crphyvne sbez, fbzr gjb srrg va yratgu, juvpu
is perpendicularly inserted into the starboard gunwale near the bow,            vf crecraqvphyneyl vafregrq vagb gur fgneobneq thajnyr arne gur obj,
for the purpose of furnishing a rest for the wooden extremity of the            sbe gur checbfr bs sheavfuvat n erfg sbe gur jbbqra rkgerzvgl bs gur
harpoon, whose other naked, barbed end slopingly projects from the prow.        unecbba, jubfr bgure anxrq, oneorq raq fybcvatyl cebwrpgf sebz gur cebj.
Thereby the weapon is instantly at hand to its hurler, who snatches it          Gurerol gur jrncba vf vafgnagyl ng unaq gb vgf uheyre, jub fangpurf vg
up as readily from its rest as a backwoodsman swings his rifle from             hc nf ernqvyl sebz vgf erfg nf n onpxjbbqfzna fjvatf uvf evsyr sebz
the wall. It is customary to have two harpoons reposing in the crotch,          gur jnyy. Vg vf phfgbznel gb unir gjb unecbbaf ercbfvat va gur pebgpu,
respectively called the first and second irons.                                 erfcrpgviryl pnyyrq gur svefg naq frpbaq vebaf.
                                                                                
But these two harpoons, each by its own cord, are both connected with           Ohg gurfr gjb unecbbaf, rnpu ol vgf bja pbeq, ner obgu pbaarpgrq jvgu
the line; the object being this: to dart them both, if possible, one            gur yvar; gur bowrpg orvat guvf: gb qneg gurz obgu, vs cbffvoyr, bar
instantly after the other into the same whale; so that if, in the coming        vafgnagyl nsgre gur bgure vagb gur fnzr junyr; fb gung vs, va gur pbzvat
drag, one should draw out, the other may still retain a hold. It is a           qent, bar fubhyq qenj bhg, gur bgure znl fgvyy ergnva n ubyq. Vg vf n
doubling of the chances. But it very often happens that owing to the            qbhoyvat bs gur punaprf. Ohg vg irel bsgra unccraf gung bjvat gb gur
instantaneous, violent, convulsive running of the whale upon receiving          vafgnagnarbhf, ivbyrag, pbaihyfvir ehaavat bs gur junyr hcba erprvivat
the first iron, it becomes impossible for the harpooneer, however               gur svefg veba, vg orpbzrf vzcbffvoyr sbe gur unecbbarre, ubjrire
lightning-like in his movements, to pitch the second iron into him.             yvtugavat-yvxr va uvf zbirzragf, gb cvgpu gur frpbaq veba vagb uvz.
Nevertheless, as the second iron is already connected with the line,            Arireguryrff, nf gur frpbaq veba vf nyernql pbaarpgrq jvgu gur yvar,
and the line is running, hence that weapon must, at all events, be              naq gur yvar vf ehaavat, urapr gung jrncba zhfg, ng nyy riragf, or
anticipatingly tossed out of the boat, somehow and somewhere; else the          nagvpvcngvatyl gbffrq bhg bs gur obng, fbzrubj naq fbzrjurer; ryfr gur
most terrible jeopardy would involve all hands. Tumbled into the water,         zbfg greevoyr wrbcneql jbhyq vaibyir nyy unaqf. Ghzoyrq vagb gur jngre,
it accordingly is in such cases; the spare coils of box line (mentioned         vg nppbeqvatyl vf va fhpu pnfrf; gur fcner pbvyf bs obk yvar (zragvbarq
in a preceding chapter) making this feat, in most instances, prudently          va n cerprqvat puncgre) znxvat guvf srng, va zbfg vafgnaprf, cehqragyl
practicable. But this critical act is not always unattended with the            cenpgvpnoyr. Ohg guvf pevgvpny npg vf abg nyjnlf hanggraqrq jvgu gur
saddest and most fatal casualties.                                              fnqqrfg naq zbfg sngny pnfhnygvrf.
                                                                                
Furthermore: you must know that when the second iron is thrown                  Shegurezber: lbh zhfg xabj gung jura gur frpbaq veba vf guebja
overboard, it thenceforth becomes a dangling, sharp-edged terror,               bireobneq, vg guraprsbegu orpbzrf n qnatyvat, funec-rqtrq greebe,
skittishly curvetting about both boat and whale, entangling the lines,          fxvggvfuyl pheirggvat nobhg obgu obng naq junyr, ragnatyvat gur yvarf,
or cutting them, and making a prodigious sensation in all directions.           be phggvat gurz, naq znxvat n cebqvtvbhf frafngvba va nyy qverpgvbaf.
Nor, in general, is it possible to secure it again until the whale is           Abe, va trareny, vf vg cbffvoyr gb frpher vg ntnva hagvy gur junyr vf
fairly captured and a corpse.                                                   snveyl pncgherq naq n pbecfr.
                                                                                
Consider, now, how it must be in the case of four boats all engaging            Pbafvqre, abj, ubj vg zhfg or va gur pnfr bs sbhe obngf nyy ratntvat
one unusually strong, active, and knowing whale; when owing to these            bar hahfhnyyl fgebat, npgvir, naq xabjvat junyr; jura bjvat gb gurfr
qualities in him, as well as to the thousand concurring accidents of            dhnyvgvrf va uvz, nf jryy nf gb gur gubhfnaq pbapheevat nppvqragf bs
such an audacious enterprise, eight or ten loose second irons may be            fhpu na nhqnpvbhf ragrecevfr, rvtug be gra ybbfr frpbaq vebaf znl or
simultaneously dangling about him. For, of course, each boat is supplied        fvzhygnarbhfyl qnatyvat nobhg uvz. Sbe, bs pbhefr, rnpu obng vf fhccyvrq
with several harpoons to bend on to the line should the first one               jvgu frireny unecbbaf gb oraq ba gb gur yvar fubhyq gur svefg bar
be ineffectually darted without recovery. All these particulars are             or varssrpghnyyl qnegrq jvgubhg erpbirel. Nyy gurfr cnegvphynef ner
faithfully narrated here, as they will not fail to elucidate several            snvgushyyl aneengrq urer, nf gurl jvyy abg snvy gb ryhpvqngr frireny
