CHAPTER 65. The Whale as a Dish.                                                PUNCGRE 65. Gur Junyr nf n Qvfu.
                                                                                
                                                                                
That mortal man should feed upon the creature that feeds his lamp, and,         Gung zbegny zna fubhyq srrq hcba gur perngher gung srrqf uvf ynzc, naq,
like Stubb, eat him by his own light, as you may say; this seems so             yvxr Fghoo, rng uvz ol uvf bja yvtug, nf lbh znl fnl; guvf frrzf fb
outlandish a thing that one must needs go a little into the history and         bhgynaqvfu n guvat gung bar zhfg arrqf tb n yvggyr vagb gur uvfgbel naq
philosophy of it.                                                               cuvybfbcul bs vg.
                                                                                
It is upon record, that three centuries ago the tongue of the Right             Vg vf hcba erpbeq, gung guerr praghevrf ntb gur gbathr bs gur Evtug
Whale was esteemed a great delicacy in France, and commanded large              Junyr jnf rfgrrzrq n terng qryvpnpl va Senapr, naq pbzznaqrq ynetr
prices there. Also, that in Henry VIIIth's time, a certain cook of the          cevprf gurer. Nyfb, gung va Urael IVVVgu'f gvzr, n pregnva pbbx bs gur
court obtained a handsome reward for inventing an admirable sauce to be         pbheg bognvarq n unaqfbzr erjneq sbe vairagvat na nqzvenoyr fnhpr gb or
eaten with barbacued porpoises, which, you remember, are a species of           rngra jvgu oneonphrq cbecbvfrf, juvpu, lbh erzrzore, ner n fcrpvrf bs
whale. Porpoises, indeed, are to this day considered fine eating. The           junyr. Cbecbvfrf, vaqrrq, ner gb guvf qnl pbafvqrerq svar rngvat. Gur
meat is made into balls about the size of billiard balls, and being well        zrng vf znqr vagb onyyf nobhg gur fvmr bs ovyyvneq onyyf, naq orvat jryy
seasoned and spiced might be taken for turtle-balls or veal balls.              frnfbarq naq fcvprq zvtug or gnxra sbe ghegyr-onyyf be irny onyyf.
The old monks of Dunfermline were very fond of them. They had a great           Gur byq zbaxf bs Qhasrezyvar jrer irel sbaq bs gurz. Gurl unq n terng
porpoise grant from the crown.                                                  cbecbvfr tenag sebz gur pebja.
                                                                                
The fact is, that among his hunters at least, the whale would by all            Gur snpg vf, gung nzbat uvf uhagref ng yrnfg, gur junyr jbhyq ol nyy
hands be considered a noble dish, were there not so much of him; but            unaqf or pbafvqrerq n aboyr qvfu, jrer gurer abg fb zhpu bs uvz; ohg
when you come to sit down before a meat-pie nearly one hundred feet             jura lbh pbzr gb fvg qbja orsber n zrng-cvr arneyl bar uhaqerq srrg
long, it takes away your appetite. Only the most unprejudiced of men            ybat, vg gnxrf njnl lbhe nccrgvgr. Bayl gur zbfg hacerwhqvprq bs zra
like Stubb, nowadays partake of cooked whales; but the Esquimaux are not        yvxr Fghoo, abjnqnlf cnegnxr bs pbbxrq junyrf; ohg gur Rfdhvznhk ner abg
so fastidious. We all know how they live upon whales, and have rare             fb snfgvqvbhf. Jr nyy xabj ubj gurl yvir hcba junyrf, naq unir ener
old vintages of prime old train oil. Zogranda, one of their most famous         byq ivagntrf bs cevzr byq genva bvy. Mbtenaqn, bar bs gurve zbfg snzbhf
doctors, recommends strips of blubber for infants, as being exceedingly         qbpgbef, erpbzzraqf fgevcf bs oyhoore sbe vasnagf, nf orvat rkprrqvatyl
juicy and nourishing. And this reminds me that certain Englishmen, who          whvpl naq abhevfuvat. Naq guvf erzvaqf zr gung pregnva Ratyvfuzra, jub
long ago were accidentally left in Greenland by a whaling vessel--that          ybat ntb jrer nppvqragnyyl yrsg va Terraynaq ol n junyvat irffry--gung
these men actually lived for several months on the mouldy scraps of             gurfr zra npghnyyl yvirq sbe frireny zbaguf ba gur zbhyql fpencf bs
whales which had been left ashore after trying out the blubber. Among           junyrf juvpu unq orra yrsg nfuber nsgre gelvat bhg gur oyhoore. Nzbat
the Dutch whalemen these scraps are called "fritters"; which, indeed,           gur Qhgpu junyrzra gurfr fpencf ner pnyyrq "sevggref"; juvpu, vaqrrq,
they greatly resemble, being brown and crisp, and smelling something            gurl terngyl erfrzoyr, orvat oebja naq pevfc, naq fzryyvat fbzrguvat
