that right. The law itself has already been set forth. But Plowdon gives        gung evtug. Gur ynj vgfrys unf nyernql orra frg sbegu. Ohg Cybjqba tvirf
us the reason for it. Says Plowdon, the whale so caught belongs to              hf gur ernfba sbe vg. Fnlf Cybjqba, gur junyr fb pnhtug orybatf gb
the King and Queen, "because of its superior excellence." And by the            gur Xvat naq Dhrra, "orpnhfr bs vgf fhcrevbe rkpryyrapr." Naq ol gur
soundest commentators this has ever been held a cogent argument in such         fbhaqrfg pbzzragngbef guvf unf rire orra uryq n pbtrag nethzrag va fhpu
matters.                                                                        znggref.
                                                                                
But why should the King have the head, and the Queen the tail? A reason         Ohg jul fubhyq gur Xvat unir gur urnq, naq gur Dhrra gur gnvy? N ernfba
for that, ye lawyers!                                                           sbe gung, lr ynjlref!
                                                                                
In his treatise on "Queen-Gold," or Queen-pinmoney, an old King's Bench         Va uvf gerngvfr ba "Dhrra-Tbyq," be Dhrra-cvazbarl, na byq Xvat'f Orapu
author, one William Prynne, thus discourseth: "Ye tail is ye Queen's,           nhgube, bar Jvyyvnz Celaar, guhf qvfpbhefrgu: "Lr gnvy vf lr Dhrra'f,
that ye Queen's wardrobe may be supplied with ye whalebone." Now this           gung lr Dhrra'f jneqebor znl or fhccyvrq jvgu lr junyrobar." Abj guvf
was written at a time when the black limber bone of the Greenland or            jnf jevggra ng n gvzr jura gur oynpx yvzore obar bs gur Terraynaq be
Right whale was largely used in ladies' bodices. But this same bone             Evtug junyr jnf ynetryl hfrq va ynqvrf' obqvprf. Ohg guvf fnzr obar
is not in the tail; it is in the head, which is a sad mistake for               vf abg va gur gnvy; vg vf va gur urnq, juvpu vf n fnq zvfgnxr sbe
a sagacious lawyer like Prynne. But is the Queen a mermaid, to be               n fntnpvbhf ynjlre yvxr Celaar. Ohg vf gur Dhrra n zreznvq, gb or
presented with a tail? An allegorical meaning may lurk here.                    cerfragrq jvgu n gnvy? Na nyyrtbevpny zrnavat znl yhex urer.
                                                                                
There are two royal fish so styled by the English law writers--the whale        Gurer ner gjb eblny svfu fb fglyrq ol gur Ratyvfu ynj jevgref--gur junyr
and the sturgeon; both royal property under certain limitations, and            naq gur fghetrba; obgu eblny cebcregl haqre pregnva yvzvgngvbaf, naq
nominally supplying the tenth branch of the crown's ordinary revenue.           abzvanyyl fhccylvat gur gragu oenapu bs gur pebja'f beqvanel erirahr.
I know not that any other author has hinted of the matter; but by               V xabj abg gung nal bgure nhgube unf uvagrq bs gur znggre; ohg ol
inference it seems to me that the sturgeon must be divided in the same          vasrerapr vg frrzf gb zr gung gur fghetrba zhfg or qvivqrq va gur fnzr
way as the whale, the King receiving the highly dense and elastic head          jnl nf gur junyr, gur Xvat erprvivat gur uvtuyl qrafr naq rynfgvp urnq
peculiar to that fish, which, symbolically regarded, may possibly be            crphyvne gb gung svfu, juvpu, flzobyvpnyyl ertneqrq, znl cbffvoyl or
humorously grounded upon some presumed congeniality. And thus there             uhzbebhfyl tebhaqrq hcba fbzr cerfhzrq pbatravnyvgl. Naq guhf gurer
seems a reason in all things, even in law.                                      frrzf n ernfba va nyy guvatf, rira va ynj.
                                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
