CHAPTER 92. Ambergris.                                                          PUNCGRE 92. Nzoretevf.
                                                                                
                                                                                
Now this ambergris is a very curious substance, and so important as             Abj guvf nzoretevf vf n irel phevbhf fhofgnapr, naq fb vzcbegnag nf
an article of commerce, that in 1791 a certain Nantucket-born Captain           na negvpyr bs pbzzrepr, gung va 1791 n pregnva Anaghpxrg-obea Pncgnva
Coffin was examined at the bar of the English House of Commons on that          Pbssva jnf rknzvarq ng gur one bs gur Ratyvfu Ubhfr bs Pbzzbaf ba gung
subject. For at that time, and indeed until a comparatively late day,           fhowrpg. Sbe ng gung gvzr, naq vaqrrq hagvy n pbzcnengviryl yngr qnl,
the precise origin of ambergris remained, like amber itself, a problem          gur cerpvfr bevtva bs nzoretevf erznvarq, yvxr nzore vgfrys, n ceboyrz
to the learned. Though the word ambergris is but the French compound for        gb gur yrnearq. Gubhtu gur jbeq nzoretevf vf ohg gur Serapu pbzcbhaq sbe
grey amber, yet the two substances are quite distinct. For amber, though        terl nzore, lrg gur gjb fhofgnaprf ner dhvgr qvfgvapg. Sbe nzore, gubhtu
at times found on the sea-coast, is also dug up in some far inland              ng gvzrf sbhaq ba gur frn-pbnfg, vf nyfb qht hc va fbzr sne vaynaq
soils, whereas ambergris is never found except upon the sea. Besides,           fbvyf, jurernf nzoretevf vf arire sbhaq rkprcg hcba gur frn. Orfvqrf,
amber is a hard, transparent, brittle, odorless substance, used for             nzore vf n uneq, genafcnerag, oevggyr, bqbeyrff fhofgnapr, hfrq sbe
mouth-pieces to pipes, for beads and ornaments; but ambergris is soft,          zbhgu-cvrprf gb cvcrf, sbe ornqf naq beanzragf; ohg nzoretevf vf fbsg,
waxy, and so highly fragrant and spicy, that it is largely used in              jnkl, naq fb uvtuyl sentenag naq fcvpl, gung vg vf ynetryl hfrq va
perfumery, in pastiles, precious candles, hair-powders, and pomatum.            creshzrel, va cnfgvyrf, cerpvbhf pnaqyrf, unve-cbjqref, naq cbznghz.
The Turks use it in cooking, and also carry it to Mecca, for the same           Gur Ghexf hfr vg va pbbxvat, naq nyfb pneel vg gb Zrppn, sbe gur fnzr
purpose that frankincense is carried to St. Peter's in Rome. Some wine          checbfr gung senaxvaprafr vf pneevrq gb Fg. Crgre'f va Ebzr. Fbzr jvar
merchants drop a few grains into claret, to flavor it.                          zrepunagf qebc n srj tenvaf vagb pynerg, gb synibe vg.
                                                                                
