times, of a Dutch village called Schmerenburgh or Smeerenberg, which            gvzrf, bs n Qhgpu ivyyntr pnyyrq Fpuzreraohetu be Fzrreraoret, juvpu
latter name is the one used by the learned Fogo Von Slack, in his great         ynggre anzr vf gur bar hfrq ol gur yrnearq Sbtb Iba Fynpx, va uvf terng
work on Smells, a text-book on that subject. As its name imports (smeer,        jbex ba Fzryyf, n grkg-obbx ba gung fhowrpg. Nf vgf anzr vzcbegf (fzrre,
fat; berg, to put up), this village was founded in order to afford a            sng; oret, gb chg hc), guvf ivyyntr jnf sbhaqrq va beqre gb nssbeq n
place for the blubber of the Dutch whale fleet to be tried out, without         cynpr sbe gur oyhoore bs gur Qhgpu junyr syrrg gb or gevrq bhg, jvgubhg
being taken home to Holland for that purpose. It was a collection of            orvat gnxra ubzr gb Ubyynaq sbe gung checbfr. Vg jnf n pbyyrpgvba bs
